# Project Standards

## 1) TypeScript Only

- Use TypeScript only for implementation code.
- New source files must be `.ts` or `.tsx`.
- Do not introduce new `.js`/`.jsx` source files unless explicitly requested.

## 2) Package Installation Policy

- **NEVER** install, add, or update any packages (via `npm`, `pnpm`, `yarn`, etc.) or modify `package.json` dependencies unless explicitly requested or approved by the user.
- Before adding or updating any npm package (once approved), verify the package on [npmjs.com](https://www.npmjs.com/).
- Use the latest **stable** release at the time of installation.
- Do not use dist-tags/ranges like `latest`, `next`, or `canary` in `package.json`; pin an explicit stable semver range (e.g. `^x.y.z`).
- Avoid pre-release versions (`alpha`, `beta`, `rc`, `next`, `canary`) unless explicitly requested.

## 3) Unauthorized File Changes

- **NEVER** create, modify, or delete files or directories that are not explicitly included in the agreed-upon plan or directly requested by the user.
- Always ask for permission before modifying files or directories outside the current task's scope.

## 4) Git Command Restrictions (Allow-list Policy)

- **Allowed for autonomous information gathering (Read-only):**
  You may freely use `git status`, `git log`, `git diff`, `git show`, `git branch` (for listing), and `git ls-files` to understand the repository state.
- **Allowed ONLY upon explicit user request:**
  Any Git command NOT listed above (including `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`, `git reset`, `git checkout`, `git restore`, `git clean`, `git stash`, `git rebase`, `git rm`, `git pull`, `git merge`, etc.) must **NEVER** be used unless explicitly requested by the user.

## 5) Timestamp Policy

- Record all timestamps in `Asia/Tokyo` timezone (JST, `+09:00`) only.

## 6) Cross-File Consistency Check

- When changing or fixing content, always check related files across the repository for consistency (terminology, roles, scope, IDs, links, and constraints).
- If related files are found, update them in the same task unless the user explicitly instructs otherwise.
- Before completing the task, verify there are no stale or conflicting definitions left in nearby artifacts (requirements, plans, stories, personas, and audit logs).

## 7) Project-Specific Skills Location

- Project-specific custom skills MUST be created and maintained under `.cursor/skills/`.
- Do NOT add project-specific custom skills under `.agents/skills/`.
- When moving existing project-specific skills, update related references in the same task.

## 8) AI Review and Merge Restriction

- AI agents must **NEVER** perform self-review approvals on pull requests they authored or updated.
- AI agents must **NEVER** merge pull requests unless the user explicitly requests the merge in the current conversation.
- Exception: pull requests created by `dependabot[bot]` may be merged by AI agents only when the user explicitly instructs the merge in the current conversation.
- Even when merge is explicitly requested, AI agents must not bypass required checks, required reviews, or branch protection rules.

## 9) Commit Scope and Completion Discipline

- **NEVER** modify files outside the explicit user request or agreed scope. If unexpected or unrelated changes are required, stop and ask for confirmation first.
- Unless the user explicitly requests otherwise, all intended changes in the current task scope must be committed before finishing the task.
- Before any commit, review changed files and confirm intent. Any unintentionally changed file must be called out to the user before commit.
- Before creating or updating a PR, run a final working-tree check (`git status --short` and `git diff --staged`) to ensure no accidental omissions or unintended files remain.

## 10) Merged PR Immutability

- **NEVER** attempt to add commits to a pull request that is already merged or closed.
- Before any push intended for an existing PR, verify the PR state is open. If the PR is merged/closed, create a new branch and a new PR instead.
- If uncertain which PR is active for a branch, check explicitly and confirm with the user before pushing.
